## 2. KEY INSIGHTS

**Structural Breakthrough:** The 18-vector threshold arises from the universal bound η(C_p⁴) = 17(p-1)+1. Since any sequence of 17(p-1)+2 elements contains a zero-sum subsequence of length ≤ p, our problem is equivalent to proving that among 18 nonzero non-proportional vectors in F_p⁴, such a subsequence exists.

**Pair-Degeneracy is the Barrier:** The fundamental obstruction to using the rank-3 theorem is **pair-degenerate collinear triples**, where one coefficient cancels another. These triples are geometrically characterized by one vector being proportional to the difference of two others. A configuration avoids all small-weight zero-sums only if every collinear triple is pair-degenerate (a **super-degenerate** set).

**Projection Dynamics:** Restricting to a fiber F_c by fixing w(v) = c projects 18 vectors to a 3-dimensional space. The proportionality structure is preserved (if v_i ∝ v_j in F_p⁴, then their projections remain non-proportional), so fiber analysis reduces to understanding rank-3 problems.

**Weight Function Flexibility:** For any fixed bound on a single fiber size, there exists a choice of linear form w (projection) that forces either:
  - Some fiber to exceed the threshold (triggering induction), or  
  - Cross-fiber collinear triples with specific fiber signatures that are generically non-degenerate.

**The 94-Case Resolution (p=5 empirical):** All residual cases after applying rank-3 and two-fiber bounds are eliminated by support-4 zero-sums (four vectors with weight < p). This suggests Chevalley-Warning congruences, when combined with rank-3 constraints, force such four-element relations to exist.

